******
[1]
Date: Fri 11 Nov 2011
Source: RIA Novosti [in Russian, machine transl., edited]
http://eco.ria.ru/danger/20111111/486167453.html


The Kyrgyz authorities would punish "those responsible" for
distributing FMD
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Prime Minister of Kyrgyzstan Omurbek Babanov ordered that urgent
measures be taken to combat the epidemic of FMD in the country, as
well as to punish those who caused the spread of the disease, a
representative of the Kyrgyzi government press service told RIA
Novosti on Friday [11 Nov 2011].

Foot and mouth disease [FMD] is a fatal infectious disease affecting
livestock and wild ungulates. According to the Ministry of Agriculture
of Kyrgyzstan, to date, infections have been reported in 62 locations
across the country, with 6000 head of cattle affected.

"The outbreak of FMD began in Kyrgyzstan in mid-September [2011], and
within 2 months it spread to several regions of the country. Despite
the action taken in October, a new strain of the pathogen was
recorded, namely 'A-Iran-5,' against which the applied vaccine does
not provide protection," he said.

According to him, Babanov instructed the Ministry of Agriculture to
take "the strictest measures against those persons responsible for the
FMD outbreak" and to provide the needed veterinary services and
manpower to all AO (local authorities in Kyrgyzstan).

According to the Ministry of Agriculture, about 2.5 million head of
cattle have been vaccinated this year against FMD in Kyrgyzstan. To
tackle the problem, funds have been diverted from other subjects such
as the prevention of sheep and goat pox.

--
